From the north end, Brian Daniels and I, along with Guy McCaskie and Peter Ginsburg in a separate vehicle, worked our way south along the west side of the Sea, checking along the way Salton City (including the abandoned marina between Salton Sea Beach and Salton City; 9:15-10:25 am).  We concluded the day by checking moderately carefully the Elmore Ranch (10:45 am – 12:45 pm).  This was my first time on this large, private ranch with limited access.  Although much of the ranch is comprised of open alfalfa fields, the ranch borders the Sea.  It was along this border that we concentrated our time, scanning the pelicans and cormorants at a point, and then checked herons at a nearby cove.  There was also one relatively large marshy cove here that had many roosting gulls and shorebirds, and a few ducks.  We also checked carefully a marshy area just behind the levee where a pair of Black-bellied Whistling-Ducks had been seen several times over the past month.  Despite our having relatively good luck finding interesting birds on this ranch, we were unable to locate the ducks.  Given that I did not specify which birds were seen at Salton City and which were at Elmore Ranch, I am entering the list using the ranch location because it appears that all of the noteworthy species, and likely most of the species in total were seen on the ranch.  It was clear, calm or with a mild breeze, and temperatures in the low 90s to low 100s.  9:15 am – 12:45 pm.----Western Whiptail - 1 (I missed a lizard that was seen by others).
